  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Immediate Impressions at Hyangilam Hermitage
  author: Hong Gwi-dal
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The window glows—another day has broken through.
    The heated floor and quilted robes lie thick and warm.
    I split the cinnamon wood to perfume cooking rice,
    Part the clouds to draw up water, cold and clear.

    The hermitage rises high above the vast ravine;
    An old monk speaks of heaven's secrets as I listen.
    One stroke of the bell rings out within the hall,
    And I, a wanderer, drift slowly into sleep.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Hyangilam (向日菴) was a hermitage in Korea known for its mountain setting and contemplative atmosphere
  - key: ''
    value: The cinnamon wood (桂) reference alludes to both the literal burning of aromatic wood and classical poetic imagery of refinement and transcendence
